  "prompt": "In genetics, what is an example of a monohybrid cross offspring?",
  "response": "A monohybrid cross is a breeding experiment between two organisms that are heterozygous for a single trait. This means each parent carries two different alleles for a particular gene, typically one dominant and one recessive. A classic example often used to illustrate a monohybrid cross is Mendel's pea plants.\n\nConsider a monohybrid cross involving the gene for plant height in pea plants, where the allele for tall plants (T) is dominant over the allele for short plants (t). If you cross two heterozygous pea plants (Tt x Tt), the possible offspring genotypes are:\n\n- TT (homozygous dominant): Tall\n- Tt (heterozygous): Tall\n- tt (homozygous recessive): Short\n\nThe phenotypic ratio of the offspring would be approximately 3:1, with three-quarters exhibiting the dominant trait (tall plants) and one-quarter exhibiting the recessive trait (short plants). This illustrates how Mendelian inheritance works in a monohybrid cross.",
